Reading census files

#list.files(path ='data/NY_Census_Data/',pattern=".csv$") # use the pattern argument to define a common pattern  for import files with regex. Here: .csv
 
# create a list from these files
list.filenames<-list.files(path ='data/NY_Census_Data/',pattern=".csv$")
list.filenames
## [1] "ACS_10.csv" "ACS_11.csv" "ACS_12.csv" "ACS_13.csv" "ACS_14.csv"
## [6] "ACS_15.csv" "ACS_16.csv" "ACS_9.csv"
# create an empty list that will serve as a container to receive the incoming files
list.data<-list()
 
# create a loop to read in your data
for (i in 1:length(list.filenames))
{
list.data[[i]]<-read.csv(paste('data/NY_Census_Data/',list.filenames[i],sep=''))
}
 
# add the names of your data to the list
names(list.data)<-list.filenames


import.multiple.csv.files<-function(mypath,mypattern,...)
{
tmp.list.1<-list.files(mypath, pattern=mypattern)
tmp.list.2<-list(length=length(tmp.list.1))
for (i in 1:length(tmp.list.1)){tmp.list.2[[i]]<-read.csv(tmp.list.1[i],...)}
names(tmp.list.2)<-tmp.list.1
tmp.list.2
}

Reading in shapefile and plotting sample plot

nyc_tract <- readOGR("data/NewYork/.","NY_New")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "data/NewYork/.", layer: "NY_New"
## with 2166 features
## It has 37 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  OID_ Field1 HD01_VD01 HD02_VD01 HD01_VD02 HD02_VD02 HD01_VD03 HD02_VD03 HD01_VD04 HD02_VD04 HD01_VD05 HD02_VD05 HD01_VD06 HD02_VD06 HD01_VD07 HD02_VD07 HD01_VD08 HD02_VD08 HD01_VD09 HD02_VD09 HD01_VD10 HD02_VD10 HD01_VD11 HD02_VD11
nyc_tract@data$GEOID<-as.character(nyc_tract@data$GEOID)


data <- select(data, GEO.id2, GEO.display.label,'2009_RentBurden','2010_RentBurden', '2011_RentBurden', '2012_RentBurden', '2013_RentBurden', '2014_RentBurden',
               '2015_RentBurden', '2016_RentBurden') %>% 
  slice(-1) %>% # census has this extra descriptive record
  rename(id=GEO.id2, geography=GEO.display.label)

data <- mutate(data, id=as.character(id),
               geography=as.character(geography))

ggtract<-fortify(nyc_tract, region = "GEOID") 

ggtract<-left_join(ggtract, data, by=c("id")) 

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = ggtract , aes(x=long, y=lat, group = group, fill=ggtract$`2009_RentBurden`), color="grey50") +
   scale_fill_gradientn(colours = c("red", "white", "cadetblue"),
                       values = c(1,0.5, .3, .2, .1, 0))+
  coord_map(xlim = c(-74.26, -73.71), ylim = c(40.49,40.92))

Looping through plots

j = 1

for (n in 9:16) {

     # create different categories/shadings of unemployment  
     ggtract$rate <- cut(as.numeric(ggtract[,n]), breaks = 5)

     # choose colours
     cbbPalette <- c("#E3D1E7","#D7B5D8","#DB8DC3","#DF65B0","#D63B83","#CE1256")
    lis = c(2009,2010,2011,2012,2013,2014,2015,2016)
     #ggplot code
     map = ggplot(ggtract, aes(long, lat, group = group)) +
     geom_polygon(aes(fill = rate), colour = alpha("white", 1/2), size = 0.2) +
     scale_fill_manual(values=cbbPalette, name = paste("RentBurden_",lis[n-8],sep = '')) +
     ylab("Latitude") +  xlab("Longitude")

     #get the date of the unemployment data to use in labeling map

     name <- names(ggtract)[n]
     g1 <- map + coord_map() #+ opts(title = name)
     ggsave(plot = g1, filename=paste('nyc_rentburden', j, '.jpg', sep = ''), height = 5, width = 6)
     j = j + 1

}

Making GIF from the images stored

p <- "nyc_rentburden%d.jpg"
out <- "nyc_op.gif"
# 10 fps gif
ffmpeg(pattern = p, output = out, rate = 10)
## arguments 'show.output.on.console', 'minimized' and 'invisible' are for Windows only
